{"cursor":"33317","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n exposes Nasonov gland (white-at tip of abdomen) releasing pheromone to entice\n swarm into an empty hive]] A 'pheromone' (from Greek ÏÎ­ÏÏ phero \"to bear\" and\n hormone, from Greek á½ÏÎ¼Î® \"impetus\") is a secreted or excreted chemical factor\n that triggers a social response in members of the same species. Pheromones are\n chemicals capable of acting outside the body of the secreting individual to\n impact the behavior of the receiving individual. There are [[alarm\n signal|alarm]] pheromones, food trail pheromones, [[sex pheromones]], and many\n others that affect behavior or physiology. Pheromones are used from basic\n unicellular prokaryotes to complex multicellular eukaryotes. Their\n use among insects has been particularly well documented. In addition, some\n vertebrates and plants communicate by using pheromones.\n","linknr":530,"url":"Pheromone","recorded":1362684890,"links":69,"instances":["animal_behavior","genetics"],"pdf":["http://jme.endocrinology-journals.org/content/22/3/207.full.pdf","http://jme.endocrinology-journals.org/content/22/3/207.full.pdf","http://evolution.anthro.univie.ac.at/institutes/urbanethology/resources/pdf/NEL220501R01_.pdf","http://evolution.anthro.univie.ac.at/institutes/urbanethology/resources/pdf/NEL220501R01_.pdf"],"categories":["Pheromones|*","Endocrinology"],"headings":["Background","Limits","Types","Evolution","Uses","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Padlock-silver.svg/20px-Padlock-silver.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Nasinov_9024.JPG/220px-Nasinov_9024.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Bug_aggregation.jpg/220px-Bug_aggregation.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.o